WHAT IS THIS KINGDOM
The domain that defines the visual pipelines, display models,
and interaction protocols for spatial computing devices. It
encompasses head-mounted displays (Apple Vision Pro, Meta Quest,
Varjo), holographic light-field displays, real-time cloud
rendering (NVIDIA CloudXR), foveated transport, and the spatial
adaptation of color appearance models. It extends GIOP's color
and luminance guarantees into three-dimensional, user-centric
viewing environments where the observer is inside the scene.

WHY IT EXISTS
Spatial computing dissolves the frame boundary. Virtual objects
must match the color, contrast, and dynamic range of the physical
world seen through passthrough cameras or optical see-through
displays. Without a perceptual foundation, AR overlays look
disconnected, HDR highlights break immersion, and motion-to-
photon latency causes discomfort. This kingdom provides the
mathematical and perceptual rules that ensure virtual content
is visually indistinguishable from reality, regardless of the
viewing device or user pose.

HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Seven sub-domains: Head-Mounted Display Architecture and
Rendering Parameters, Foveated Rendering and Transport, Varifocal
and Light-Field Displays, Real-Time Cloud Rendering (CloudXR),
Spatial Color Appearance and Passthrough Matching, Timewarp and
Synchronization, and Holographic and Holoportation Displays.
Each section defines the device models, performance constraints,
and color pipeline integration points.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
Apple Vision Pro rendering pipelines, NVIDIA CloudXR streaming
servers, Unreal Engine and Unity XR plug-ins, foveated video
codecs, holographic telepresence systems, and calibration tools
for spatial displays.

WHO USES IT
Spatial computing engineers, XR pipeline architects, immersive
experience designers, and color scientists extending their
work to 3D environments.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Eliminates the visual seam between real and virtual by enforcing
a device-independent spatial color pipeline. Prevents motion
sickness from incorrect luminance adaptation by modeling the
user's visual state. Guarantees that a spatial experience
authored on one headset renders identically on another, with
the same ACES-based color fidelity. Provides the latency and
bandwidth models for cloud-rendered immersive content that meets
broadcast quality standards.

1. HEAD-MOUNTED DISPLAY ARCHITECTURE AND RENDERING PARAMETERS
An HMD renders two views with asymmetric projections and applies
lens distortion correction.

Apple Vision Pro reference specifications (2026):
  - Panel: micro-OLED, 3660 x 3200 pixels per eye (nominal),
    2200 x 2200 rendering resolution per eye (foveated transport).
  - Frame rate: 30 fps nominal, up to 60 fps; platform refresh
    96 Hz with timewarp.
  - Color: Rec.709 8-bit for streaming; P3-D65 10-bit for local
    and high-quality immersive playback.
  - Peak luminance: 1000 cd/m^2 (HDR highlights), 100 cd/m^2
    typical full-screen.
  - Passthrough: stereo color cameras, 12 ms latency, matched
    to display color primaries.

General HMD projection model (per eye):
  Projection matrix: defined by asymmetric frustum with
  left, right, top, bottom, near, far. The view matrix
  includes interpupillary distance (IPD) offset and per-eye
  pose. Lens distortion is modeled by a radial polynomial
  (Brown-Conrady) applied per color channel to correct
  chromatic aberration.

GIOP mandates that any HMD rendering engine output linear
ACEScg color, then apply the ODT specific to that headset's
display characteristics. The ODT includes:
  - The display EOTF (typically PQ or a modified gamma for
    OLED).
  - Gamut mapping from ACEScg to the display's native gamut
    (P3 or wider).
  - Lens distortion correction compensation.

2. FOVEATED RENDERING AND TRANSPORT
To save bandwidth and computation, only the region around the
gaze point is rendered at full resolution.

Foveation model: the visual acuity falls off with eccentricity
(e) from the fovea. Acuity threshold A(e) is approximately:
  A(e) = A_0 / (1 + k * e)
where A_0 is foveal resolution (60 pixels per degree) and k
determines fall-off rate. The rendering resolution per region
is set to match this acuity, typically using a log-polar or
multi-resolution grid.

Foveated video encoding (e.g., for cloud-rendered streams):
  - The frame is partitioned into a high-resolution central
    tile (20 degree field) and progressively lower-resolution annuli.
  - Each tile is encoded with a quality factor proportional to
    the required acuity.
  - Eye tracking data is sent as metadata; the decoder composites
    the tiles, updating within the motion-to-photon latency
    budget (approximately 10-20 ms).

GIOP defines the foveated transport container: a single video
stream carrying the tiles, with an SEI message per frame
specifying the gaze point (normalized 2D coordinates) and
a timestamp. The color encoding of each tile is in a GIOP
log space (ACEScct) to exploit perceptual uniformity for
compression. The decoder inverses the log, applies the headset
ODT, and composites the tiles into the final viewports.

3. VARIFOCAL AND LIGHT-FIELD DISPLAYS
Varifocal displays adjust the focal plane to match the vergence
of the eyes, solving the vergence-accommodation conflict.

Models: mechanically movable lenses, liquid crystal lenses, or
multi-plane focal stacks (up to 4 planes) with depth-weighted
blending. Depth maps per frame drive the focal plane selection.

Light-field HMDs: use microlens arrays or holographic optical
elements to project a 4D light-field, allowing the eye to
accommodate naturally. Rendering pipeline: generate a set of
viewpoints (angular samples), each rendered in ACEScg, then
interleaved and displayed. The display's EOTF is applied after
the light-field reconstruction.

GIOP color pipeline for multifocal and light-field HMDs:
  - Depth-dependent tone mapping: objects at different depths
    may have different effective brightness due to the optical
    stack's attenuation. The ODT includes a depth-dependent
    luminance model.
  - Color calibration: each focal plane or angular sample may
    have slightly different color reproduction. GIOP requires
    per-plane/per-view color matrices stored in the headset
    profile to equalize them to a common P3-D65 reference.

4. REAL-TIME CLOUD RENDERING (CloudXR)
NVIDIA CloudXR 6.0 (2026) enables server-side rendering of high-
fidelity immersive content streamed to thin clients.

Pipeline:
  a. Application renders frames in ACEScg on a cloud GPU
     (e.g., RTX 5090).
  b. Frames are tone-mapped by the server to the target
     display's color space using an ODT appropriate for the
     specific headset model.
  c. Encoded with HEVC or AV1 at very low latency (tuned for
     I-frame-only or short GOP, zero B-frames).
  d. Streamed over 5G-Advanced or Wi-Fi 7 to the headset.
  e. Decoded, lens-distortion corrected, timewarped, and
     displayed.

Latency budget (glass-to-glass): < 20 ms to prevent motion
sickness. GIOP defines the maximum accumulated color processing
latency to be < 2 ms, requiring heavily optimized ODT shaders
and hardware-accelerated LUTs.

GIOP streaming profile: the server sends an SDP (Session
Description Protocol) containing the headset's GIOP profile
hash, display primaries, EOTF, and current ambient illuminance
(from the headset's light sensor). The server selects the
appropriate ODT and surround adaptation model.

5. SPATIAL COLOR APPEARANCE AND PASSTHROUGH MATCHING
In passthrough AR, the viewer sees the real world through cameras.
The virtual content must match the real world in brightness, color,
and contrast.

Passthrough camera pipeline:
  a. Cameras capture the environment with a known IDT to ACEScg.
  b. The virtual content is rendered in ACEScg.
  c. Both are composited in ACEScg.
  d. The composite is transformed by the headset's ODT to the
     display.

Challenges: the camera's dynamic range may differ from the
display's, requiring local tone mapping that respects the
real-world luminance. GIOP defines a "passthrough match ODT"
that applies a spatially varying tone curve: where the real-world
luminance exceeds display peak, highlights are rolled off; where
it is below, the display's native black level is compensated
by adding a dither pattern matched to the HVS threshold.

Surround adaptation: the user's adaptation luminance changes as
they move. The headset provides an ambient light estimate (lux).
The CAM16 surround parameters are adjusted dynamically:
  - F (surround impact) from 1.0 (dark) to 0.8 (dim) to 0.6
    (average) based on ambient illuminance.
  - c (chromatic induction) similarly scaled.
This ensures that virtual objects appear consistently colored
regardless of the real-world background.

6. TIMEWARP AND SYNCHRONIZATION
Timewarp (Asynchronous Spacewarp) reprojects the last rendered
frame to match the latest head pose just before scanout, reducing
perceived latency.

Algorithm:
  - The application renders left and right eye views at time t0.
  - At scanout time t1, the actual head pose is sampled.
  - The rendered image is warped using a homography derived from
    the rotational difference between t0 and t1 poses.
  - For translational motion, depth-aware reprojection is used:
    each pixel is treated as a 3D point and re-projected.

Color correctness during timewarp:
  - The warp must operate in linear light to avoid edge artifacts.
    If the rendered image has an OETF applied, it is first
    inverse-transformed to linear ACEScg, warped, then re-encoded
    with the OETF.
  - GIOP mandates that timewarp hardware support at least 16-bit
    floating-point linear precision to avoid banding.

Synchronization of multiple devices (multi-user spatial):
  PTP (IEEE 1588) synchronizes all headsets, rendering servers,
  and audio devices to a common sub-microsecond clock. GIOP
  timestamps every rendered frame with the TAI time and the
  predicted display scanout time, enabling a shared spatial
  experience with zero perceptible drift.

7. HOLOGRAPHIC AND HOLOPORTATION DISPLAYS
Holographic displays reconstruct the full light-field of a scene,
allowing multiple viewers to see correct perspective without
headsets.

Technologies: spatial light modulators (SLMs) with phase-only
modulation, tensor displays (stacked LCDs), and acoustic-
optical modulators. They reproduce the scene's wavefront.

Color reproduction in holographic displays:
  - Three primary wavelengths (typ. 638 nm, 520 nm, 450 nm)
    are modulated separately.
  - The diffraction efficiency varies by wavelength; a color
    calibration matrix maps the requested ACEScg color to
    the SLM drive levels.
  - GIOP treats the holographic display as an ODT with a
    per-wavelength primary matrix and a diffraction efficiency
    compensation LUT.

Holoportation: real-time volumetric capture of a remote person
displayed as a hologram. The capture side uses Kingdom 10
volumetric reconstruction. The display side renders the
volumetric stream using the holographic display's ODT. GIOP
defines the end-to-end latency and color pipeline for
holoportation:
  - Capture to display latency < 200 ms for natural conversation.
  - The AMF from the capture side is transmitted to the display
    side, ensuring the color pipeline is end-to-end consistent.

